    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter May 4th with a clear focal point in the outfield: **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (80.98) is our strongest play by a significant margin. Facing Chase Petty\u2014who carries a generous 6.57 xERA\u2014**Pete Crow-Armstrong** benefits from a massive 19% boost in SP skill and a favorable dynamic platoon advantage. While his spot in the eighth hole typically suppresses value, the combination of a high-ceiling matchup and potential wind-aided production makes him our premier start. **Trea Turner** (66.43) and **Carson Benge** (67.24) also provide elite stability, though **Carson Benge** warrants close monitoring due to a 34% rain risk that could threaten his usage in a favorable park environment against Tomoyuki Sugano.\n\nOur optimizer faced a difficult internal deliberation regarding **Caleb Durbin**, who ultimately missed the cut with a 39.11 score. While **Caleb Durbin** remains an elite stolen base asset, his matchup against Tarik Skubal (2.76 xERA) proved too daunting. The severe penalty for Skubal\u2019s elite SP skill, combined with the lack of batting order security in the ninth spot, pushed **Caleb Durbin** below our threshold. Elsewhere, we are leaning into platoon advantages where possible; **Dillon Dingler** (54.63) receives a 14% lift from his platoon profile against Payton Tolle, and **Yordan Alvarez** (60.60) remains a must-start despite facing a formidable arm in Yoshinobu Yamamoto, buoyed by his elite xwOBA of .427. \n\nThe roster remains constrained by the continued absences of **Christian Yelich** and **Lars Nootbaar** on the IL, as well as **Zac Veen**\u2019s current assignment in Albuquerque. We will rely on the middle infield depth provided by **Chase Meidroth** and **Hyeseong Kim** to bridge the gap, though **Hyeseong Kim** faces a challenging afternoon against Steven Okert. As lineups finalize, we remain prepared to adjust should **Gary Sanchez**, **Kazuma Okamoto**, **Junior Caminero**, **Kyle Schwarber**, **Luke Raley**, or **Colt Keith** see their projected lineup positions fluctuate, as the majority of our bottom-of-the-order hitters rely heavily on maintaining their projected spots to provide positive efficiency.",
